Respiratory Emergencies

Dr Iain Crossingham

Consultant in Respiratory and Intensive Care Medicine
East Lancashire Hospitals NHS Trust

Agenda

  • Approach to the acutely breathless patient
    • Causes of breathlessness
    • What to do
  • Oxygen and oxygen saturations
  • Reliever inhalers
  • Selected chest disease
  • Tracheostomies and the home ventilator patient

Causes of acute breathlessness

  • Immediate to minutes
    • Airway problem
    • Pulmonary embolus (“blood clot”)
    • Pneumothorax (“collapsed lung”)
    • Heart failure
    • (Hyperventilation)
  • Minutes to hours or longer
    • Worsening of chronic lung or heart problems (asthma, COPD, etc.)
    • Chest infections, pneumonia
    • Acidosis

At a cardiac arrest, the first procedure is to take your own pulse

Samuel Shem, House of God

Management of breathing problems

  • Keep the situation calm
  • Are you safe to approach?
  • Check the airway is patent
  • Patient position — probably sitting
  • Oxygen if indicated
  • Give reliever inhaler if patient has one
    • this will normally be blue (in the UK)
    • spacer?
  • Coach breathing if necessary
  • Keep the situation calm

Oxygen and oxygen saturations

  • The main function of the heart, the lungs and the blood is to deliver oxygen to other parts of the body
  • Without oxygen, cells of the body die
  • Red blood cells carry oxygen attached to haemoglobin molecules

Oxygen saturations

Oxygen “sats” are a measure of how “full up” the haemoglobin is with oxygen

Using a pulse oximeter

  • No value giving more oxygen if sats in high 90s
  • Usual sats target 94-98%
  • Beware chronic chest patients (eg. COPD) — some will need lower sats (88-92%)

Inhalers

Airways disease

  • Narrowing of airways so patient struggles to get air in and out
  • In “classical” asthma this is caused by an allergic type mechanism and the airways go back to normal between attacks

Other airways diseases

  • The airways don't go back to normal between attacks
  • Chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)
  • Bronchiectasis, cystic fibrosis, sarcoidosis, bronchiolitis obliterans, lymphangioleiomyomatosis, etc.

Pneumothorax

Pulmonary embolus

Hyperventilation

  • Be very, very careful diagnosing this
  • Many patients have unhelpful breathing patterns, particularly during times of crisis
  • Many serious conditions mimic hyperventilation
    • eg. a build up of acid in the blood in diabetes or acute alcohol intoxication will cause a fast breathing rate and maybe the sensation of breathlessness

Tracheostomies

  • A tube into the patient's trachea (“windpipe”)
  • Can become blocked
  • Give oxygen to the face and the neck
  • Remove the inner tube if present in acutely breathless patients
  • Don't take the outer tube out

Tracheostomy tube

Home ventilators

Breathless and home ventilator

  • Generally — put it on and plug it in
  • Don't try and change any settings
  • There may be a port on the mask or machine that will connect to oxygen tubing
  • Completely ventilator dependent patients may need “bagging” if the the ventilator fails — their carers will be trained

Conclusions

  • Keep the situation calm
  • Remember the airway
  • Oxygen (94-98%, chronic chest disease maybe 88-92%)
  • Reliever inhaler
  • Coach breathing
